# Source layer boundaries

Use the project source layering to keep platform code isolated and cross-platform behavior maintainable.

## Target ownership

- `src/main.cpp`: thin launcher only.
- `src/app/`: startup/shutdown orchestration.
- `src/core/`: platform-neutral logic.
- `src/ui/`: UI composition.
- `src/platform/`: GLFW/OpenGL bootstrap and OS-specific behavior.

## Dependency constraints

- `core` must not depend on ImGui, GLFW, OpenGL, or OS APIs.
- `ui` may depend on `core` and ImGui but must not include OS-specific implementation files.
- `platform` owns OS-specific branches and OpenGL/GLFW context setup.
- `app` composes `core`, `ui`, and `platform`; avoid duplicating bootstrap logic elsewhere.

## Editing guidance

- When adding cross-platform behavior, prefer adapter extraction in `src/platform/*` over expanding shared `#ifdef` trees.
- Keep CMake target links aligned with layer boundaries (`core -> ui/platform -> app` composition, not inverse).
- If a file naturally violates current ownership, move it to the correct layer instead of adding exceptions.

Reference: `docs/standards/2026-05-01_CROSS_PLATFORM_STRUCTURE_GUIDE.md` and `AGENTS.md`.
